body:
For the record, it seems manually "enforcing" the symmetry in the calibration ranges restore performances:

```python
calibration_ranges = calibrator.compute_range()

# here v[0] == v[1], let's chnge it to -v[0]
calibration_ranges = {k: (-v[0], v[1]) for k, v in calibrations_ranges.items()}
```
Yes, TRT only supports symmetric quantization.

issue.title: Add support of generating symmetric/asymmetric tensor's range for calibration

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Add support of generating symmetric/asymmetric tensor's range for quantization calibration.

- When setting "symmetric" with either calibration method, `create_calibrator(... ,extra_options={'symmetric': True})`. The final range of tensor will be explicitly set to symmetric to central point "0".

- When setting "asymmetric" with either calibration method, `create_calibrator(... ,extra_options={'symmetric': False})`. the final range of tensor won't be explicitly set to symmetric to central point "0". (For MinMax method, the final range is real minimum value and maximum value. For Entropy/Percentile, the final range is calculated based on the given approach.)

**Motivation and Context**
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here. https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/10571
